article.description: Caity Matter set a school record for career 3s and scored 19 points to help Ohio State (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) to an 83-60 victory over UCLA (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP).
article.headline: Matter sets Ohio State record for career 3-pointers
article.linkText: Buckeyes' Matter sets record in UCLA blowout
article.story:
COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- On a night when the biggest Ohio State field goal was a 3-pointer, coach Jim Foster said the Buckeyes were pumping up way too many long shots.

Caity Matter set a school record for career 3s and scored 19 points to help Ohio State (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) to an 83-60 victory over UCLA (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) on Tuesday night.

The win was the eighth in a row for the Buckeyes (11-1), who got 20 points and 12 rebounds from Jessica Davenport and 17 points from Brandie Hoskins.

Foster was upset that his team was shooting too much from the outside in the first half instead of going inside to the 6-foot-4 Davenport.

"We were too perimeter-oriented in the first half, too quick to shoot the ball," Foster said. "We have a pretty good inside player. Then we re-established ourselves and got our identity back."

The Buckeyes finished 8-of-23 on 3-pointers but 21-of-33 (64 percent) inside the arc.

Lindsey Pluimer had 16 points, Lisa Willis 15 and Noelle Quinn 11 for UCLA (6-3), which lost for the second time in three nights to a Big Ten opponent.

The Bruins fell 78-63 at Illinois on Sunday. Starting point guard Nikki Blue, averaging 9.9 points and 4.9 assists, sustained a head injury in that game that prevented her from playing against Ohio State. UCLA issued a statement that said Blue was experiencing "concussion-like symptoms."

Matter broke the Ohio State mark when she hit a 3-pointer in transition at the 14-minute mark of the opening half off an assist from Ashley Allen. That gave Matter 219 3s, snapping a tie with Katie Smith. She later added two more from beyond the arc.

"I've said since the beginning that if the shot goes in and we win the game, I'm happy," the senior guard said. "Winning is all I'm worried about."

Ohio State, shooting 55 percent for the season, hit 29-of-56 for 52 percent.

"They're a very good team," UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said. "We've played some ranked teams (Texas, Purdue). To be honest, they're the best we've faced this year."

The Buckeyes led by as many as 27 points in the second half and the edge never dropped below 12 after the break.

Almost exactly a year ago, UCLA routed the Buckeyes 71-56 in Pauley Pavilion.

"Last year we got down and were in a funk the whole time," Davenport said. "This year everybody played their roles and did what we had to do to win."

Willis had a costly technical foul in the second half and pretended as if she were going to throw the ball at an official at one point during the first half.

With the Buckeyes leading 48-36 with 13 minutes remaining, Matter was fouled on a drive and hit both free throws. After Willis threw a crosscourt pass out of bounds, Hoskins scored on a baseline drive and was fouled by Pluimer. As the official signaled the call, Willis was called for the technical.

"Maybe we said a little too much to our friends with the stripes," Olivier said with a grin.

Matter then hit the two technical free throws and Hoskins completed the three-point play to push the lead to 55-36 with 12:28 left.

Despite hitting eight shots in a row during a 5½-minute span, the Bruins still trailed 40-26 at the break.

The Buckeyes came at UCLA in waves, with nine players scoring and eight playing double-figure minutes.

"We've got a lot of players who can come in off the bench and do something," Foster said of his team's depth. "They all have different strengths and values."
